04749nam a22006615i 9781782042051DE-B159720240306010644.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20142014xxk    fo  d z      eng d  a97817820420517 a10.1515/97817820420512doi  a(DE-B1597)676468  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxkcUK 4aPR2045b.E35 2014 7aLIT0110002bisacsh04a823/.2223  aHH 74452rvk0(DE-625)rvk/49682:118521 aEdlich-Muth, Miriam, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aMalory and his European Contemporaries :bAdapting Late Medieval Arthurian Romance Collections /cMiriam Edlich-Muth.31aWoodbridge, Suffolk : bBoydell and Brewer, c[2014] 1bD.S.Brewer, c[2014] 4c©2014  a1 online resource (199 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aArthurian Studies ;v8100tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgements -- tIntroduction -- t1 The Adaptation Process -- t2 Style and Narrative Strategy -- t3 Chronological and Genealogical Structures in the Morte Darthur, the Buch Der Abenteuer and the Tavola Ritonda -- t4 Narrative Plot Development in the Morte Darthur, the Buch Der Abenteuer and the Tavola Ritonda -- t5 ‘The Best Knight in the World’: Adapting Character Constellations -- tConclusion -- tAppendix: Note on the Texts and Manuscripts -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aA reconsideration of Arthurian compilations in the late middle ages, looking at the complex ways in which they reshape their material for new audiences.The late-medieval adaptions and compilations of the Arthurian story are a European phenomenon that has sparked both mystification and controversy. Often dismissed as nostalgic recreations that attempt to halt the literary tide, these ambitious projects saw adaptors from across Western Europe combining a vast array of prose and verse sources from different languages into encyclopedic narrative chronologies of King Arthur and his court. Ranging from ornate verse adaptations to heavily condensed prose works, the resulting texts reflect a process of translating, cutting and arranging Arthurian material into new literary incarnations, which nonetheless retain recognisable versions of the Arthurian story. This study re-evaluates Malory's Morte Darthur and four broadly contemporary European romance collections, including Jean Gonnot's French BN.fr.112 manuscript, Ulrich Fuetrer's German Buch der Abenteuer, the Dutch Lancelot Compilation, and the Italian Tavola Ritonda, in the context of this adaptive process. In doing so, it investigates how the adaptors respond to the shared structural and stylistic challenges of incorporating new material into the well-known story of King Arthur and comes to intriguing conclusions about the ways in which the narrative demands of late Arthurian adaptations invited authors to populate the Arthuriancourt with new and more complex protagonists. Miriam Edlich-Muth currently teaches Old and Middle English language and literature at the University of Cambridge.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aArthurian romancesxAdaptations. 0aArthurian romancesxHistory and criticism. 0aLiterature, MedievalxHistory and criticism. 4aMedieval Literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Medieval.2bisacsh  aArthurian compilations.  aEuropean romance.  aKing Arthur.  aMiriam Edlich-Muth.  aOld English literature.  acourt protagonists.  alate medieval Europe.  aliterary adaptations.  anarrative chronologies.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2014z978311143136940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978178204205140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781782042051423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781782042051/origin